===Etymology===
{{etyl|yi|en}} {{m|yi|ייִדיש|sc=Hebr}}, from ''Yidish Daytsh'', from {{etyl|gmh|en}} {{m|gmh|jüdisch diutsch||[[Jewish]] [[German]]}}, cognate with German {{m|de|jüdisch||Jewish}}.

Since Jewish Germans (or Yiddish) had to exist before a Yiddish language could be created, the term is probably Middle High German, rather than Yiddish.

